---
import DocsLayout from '../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { label: 'Why Bedrock', href: '#why-bedrock' },
  { label: 'The Headliners', href: '#the-headliners' },
  { label: 'The Full Toolkit', href: '#the-full-toolkit' },
  { label: 'How It Fits', href: '#how-it-fits' },
  { label: 'Built to Grow', href: '#built-to-grow' },
  { label: 'Start Building', href: '#start-building' }
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="sf-bedrock - enterprise Apex that stays readable"
  description="sf-bedrock is a Salesforce architecture toolkit: framework-level Async, EventRelay, Scheduler, and REST patterns backed by small testable Apex tools."
  eyebrow="Salesforce Architecture Toolkit"
  sections={sections}
>
  <Fragment slot="header">
    <h1>Enterprise Apex frameworks, without framework fog.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      sf-bedrock gives Salesforce teams a small set of readable frameworks for
      background work, durable events, recurring jobs, and routed REST APIs.
      Around them is a practical toolkit for fast tests, clean data seams, and
      platform-safe automation.
    </p>
    <div class="pill-row" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
      <span class="pill">Async</span>
      <span class="pill">EventRelay</span>
      <span class="pill">Scheduler</span>
      <span class="pill">REST</span>
      <span class="pill">Database-Free Tests</span>
      <span class="pill">Dependency Injection</span>
    </div>
    <div class="pill-row" style="margin-top: 1.5rem; gap: 0.6rem;">
      <a class="button button-primary" href="/getting-started">Get Started</a>
      <a class="button button-secondary" href="/async">Explore Async</a>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <section class="doc-section" id="why-bedrock">
    <h2>Why Bedrock</h2>
    <p>
      Enterprise Salesforce code needs structure, but structure should not bury
      the business logic. Bedrock separates the big repeatable platform problems
      into frameworks, then keeps the day-to-day helpers small enough to adopt
      one at a time.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Frameworks for platform pressure</h3>
        <p>
          Use shared patterns for async work, events, schedules, and APIs
          instead of rebuilding platform edge-case handling in every service.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Tools for everyday code</h3>
        <p>
          Keep records, queries, DML, cache, flags, and trigger flow testable
          without dragging heavy ceremony into production classes.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Tests that stay fast</h3>
        <p>
          Mock reads, writes, cache, limits, and scheduled or async boundaries
          so unit tests prove behavior without slow database setup.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Apex humans can maintain</h3>
        <p>
          Bedrock favors linear, low-ceremony code. The seams are explicit, the
          names are plain, and each layer has a job.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="the-headliners">
    <h2>The Headliners</h2>
    <p>
      These are Bedrock's framework-level entry points. Start here when you are
      solving a whole platform shape, not just cleaning up a single line of Apex.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/async">Async</a></h3>
        <p>
          Record-driven background work with tracked status, tuned batches,
          bounded retry, priority, staging, and multithreaded throughput when a
          straight Queueable chain is not enough.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/event-relay">EventRelay</a></h3>
        <p>
          Durable Platform Event publication and ingestion. Payloads become
          tracked work items, lanes preserve order, and handlers or publishers
          can retry without hiding failures in trigger transactions.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/scheduler">Scheduler</a></h3>
        <p>
          One fixed heartbeat drives metadata-configured logical jobs, keeping
          recurring Apex work visible without spending scheduled-job slots on
          every task.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/rest">REST</a></h3>
        <p>
          A versioned Apex REST gateway that routes metadata-configured endpoint
          roots into focused classes, with request context parsing and a testable
          endpoint surface.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="the-full-toolkit">
    <h2>The Full Toolkit</h2>
    <p>
      The rest of Bedrock supports those frameworks and improves normal Apex
      service code. Each tool is deliberately narrow, mockable, and useful on
      its own.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/test-data">TestData</a></strong>
        <span>Build realistic in-memory SObjects, including Ids, formulas, audit fields, and parent relationships.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/dml">DML</a> / <a href="/query">Query</a></strong>
        <span>Route writes and reads through small seams so tests can assert behavior without touching the database.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/selector">Selector</a></strong>
        <span>Reusable Id-based data access with transaction caching and cache-key discipline.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/trigger-handler">TriggerHandler</a></strong>
        <span>Centralize trigger context dispatch so domain hooks stay focused on lifecycle behavior.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/record-buffer">RecordBuffer</a></strong>
        <span>Stage records across a transaction, then flush grouped inserts and updates at a controlled point.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/generic">Generic</a></strong>
        <span>Read, write, coerce, and map deeply nested untyped JSON without a maze of casts and key checks.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/feature-flag">FeatureFlag</a></strong>
        <span>Metadata-driven toggles that fail closed and remain easy to override in tests.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/platform-cache">PlatformCache</a></strong>
        <span>Use org and session cache through a mockable wrapper instead of binding tests to platform cache behavior.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/limiter">Limiter</a></strong>
        <span>Guard work with named limits and a mockable contract for tests that need to prove throttling behavior.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/pluck">Pluck</a></strong>
        <span>Turn record lists into deduped Id sets that feed list-driven services and framework APIs.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="how-it-fits">
    <h2>How It Fits</h2>
    <p>
      Bedrock works best when each layer owns a clear kind of responsibility.
      The frameworks coordinate platform behavior. The tools keep the code
      inside those layers readable, replaceable, and easy to test.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Domain</h3>
        <p>
          Triggers and record lifecycle automation stay thin with
          <a href="/trigger-handler">TriggerHandler</a>,
          <a href="/record-buffer">RecordBuffer</a>, and list helpers such as
          <a href="/pluck">Pluck</a>.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Service</h3>
        <p>
          Business services coordinate work through <a href="/dml">DML</a>,
          <a href="/query">Query</a>, feature flags, cache, and the framework
          that matches the platform problem.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Operations</h3>
        <p>
          <a href="/async">Async</a>, <a href="/event-relay">EventRelay</a>,
          and <a href="/scheduler">Scheduler</a> make background work visible
          enough to tune, retry, and support.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Interface</h3>
        <p>
          <a href="/rest">REST</a> keeps API routing in one gateway, while UI
          controllers and endpoint classes stay focused on adapting requests to
          services.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="built-to-grow">
    <h2>Built to Grow</h2>
    <p>
      Bedrock grows by turning proven repeatable patterns into small,
      inspectable libraries. The current framework set covers background work,
      events, scheduled jobs, and REST APIs. The roadmap extends the same
      approach into data services only when the source and metadata are ready.
    </p>
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Adopt by pressure, not by checklist</strong>
      <p>
        Pick the framework or tool that matches the problem in front of you.
        Bedrock is a toolkit, not a mandate to replace every pattern at once.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="pill-row">
      <span class="pill">Implemented Frameworks</span>
      <span class="pill">Composable Tools</span>
      <span class="pill">Data Roadmap</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="start-building">
    <h2>Start Building</h2>
    <p>
      If you are evaluating Bedrock, begin with the testing foundation:
      <code>TestData</code>, <code>DML</code>, and <code>Query</code>. Once
      those seams feel natural, reach for the framework that matches your next
      platform problem.
    </p>
    <div class="utility-panel">
      <div>
        <h3>Ready in minutes</h3>
        <p>
          Start with the onboarding guide, then jump into Async when you want to
          see the full framework shape.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="pill-row" style="gap: 0.6rem;">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/getting-started">Getting Started</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/async">Async Framework</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
